###### Other points:

I was able to brue force it and do it in O(N^4). However according to the interviewer there was a O(N^3) solution as well

O(N^3) solution:

Let say there is a horizontal line pair (a, b): {assume distance between them is d}  -> total O(N^2) pairs

1. Find vertical lines that intersect this pair and store their x coordinate in hashmap -> O(N) lines
2. We need the x coordinates which are at distance d from each other therefore:
   iterate over the hashmap and let say current coordinate is curr then find whether there is a  coordinate (curr-d) in it.

That's it.
```
int getNumberOfSquares(vector<Line> lines, vector<Line> perpendicularLines){
    int res = 0;
	for(int i=0; i<lines.size(); i++){
	    for(int j=i+1; j<lines.size(); j++){
	        // distance between line
	        int d = abs(lines[j].start.y - lines[i].start.y);
	        // hashmap
	        unordered_map<int, int> mp;
	        // storing the x coordinate
	        for(int k=0; k<perpendicularLines.size(); k++){
	            if(intersect(lines[i], lines[j], perpendicularLines[k])){ // assuming there is a method which finds whether there is intersect in O(1)
	                mp[perpendicularLines[k].start.x] = 1;
	            }
	        }
	        // finding the vertical pairs that form a square
	        for(auto curr: mp){
	            res += mp[curr->first - d];
	        }
	    }
	}
	return res;
}
```
Time complexity: N^2 * (2 * N) ~ O(N^3)
